# 3 · DevOps

## 3.1 Building everything with one command

The developer experience stands on three layers, each with one job:

.var {headers}
   - Layer
   - Its one job

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - **just**
      - The front door. Every workflow is a `just <recipe>` — short to type, easy to remember.
    - - **mise**
      - The single source of truth for tool versions (Node, Python, Rust, uv, moon), identical on every machine.
    - - **moon**
      - Per-project tasks — `build` / `test` / `lint` / `audit` / `deps` — with caching and "only what changed" detection.

The rule we never break: *don't trust whatever happens to be on your `PATH`*. Every tool is resolved
through `mise`, and every package is declared exactly once in `.moon/workspace.yml`, with everything
else — installs, cleans, the task graph — derived from that one list. That is what keeps a mixed
TypeScript / Python / Rust build behaving like a single, tidy project instead of three.

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
    How the three layers cooperate, and how adding a service is a one-line change:
    [The Toolchain: mise, moon & just](../../dev/Developer-Guide/toolchain/).

## 3.2 Containers, and where they run

Each service ships its own **two-stage Dockerfile** — one stage compiles, the final stage carries
only the runtime and the built artifact — and refreshes its base-OS packages at build time so it
clears the registry scan. The same images run in two places:

- **Docker Compose, on your laptop.** Each service's compose files are discovered and merged
  automatically. A service sits on a shared gateway network *and* a private database network, which
  enforces the database-per-service rule *physically* — the twin service simply cannot reach the
  auth database.
- **Kubernetes, in production.** Stateless services run as **Deployments**, the databases and Redis as
  **StatefulSets** with their own persistent volumes; an **nginx Ingress** routes by URL prefix,
  `initContainers` hold a service back until its database answers, and secrets are created on the
  cluster from a local `.env` and never go anywhere near Git.

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
    Cluster manifests, ingress rewriting and rolling updates:
    [Deployment & Kubernetes](../../dev/Developer-Guide/deployment/). The local compose layering:
    [Docker Compose Orchestration](../../dev/Developer-Guide/docker-compose/).

## 3.3 Branching, and continuous deployment

We keep the branching model boring on purpose. There is **one long-lived branch, `master`**. All the
real work happens on short feature branches, and the only way into `master` is a **pull request** —
reviewed, and green on the CI gate. Direct pushes are blocked.

The important part is what happens *after* a merge: **every pull request that reaches `master` is
deployed**. There is no separate "release day". The moment a PR lands, the pipeline cuts a version,
builds and scans the images, and publishes them to the registry that production runs from — so the
freshest `master` is also the freshest deployment. That is **continuous deployment**, and it is why
the commit message is treated as a real input to the build rather than a note to ourselves.

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
    The full workflow and the golden rules:
    [Contributing & Golden Rules](../../dev/Developer-Guide/contributing/#the-contribution-workflow).
    Commit and branch conventions:
    [Naming Conventions](../../dev/Developer-Guide/naming-conventions/).

## 3.4 The pipeline

CI hangs off a **single aggregated gate** (`CI Gate / CI Passed`). One path-filter runs first, then
the work fans out — in parallel, and *only for whatever actually changed* — to each service's checks
(auth, chat, twin, sensor, socket, notification, contracts, client, agent) plus Docker, Kubernetes,
workflow-lint and infra. The gate makes its call as a **whitelist**: every leg has to come back
`success` or `skipped`, and the fan-out itself must have succeeded, so an unexpected state can never
slip through as green.

Security isn't a separate stage — it's woven in:

- **Dependencies** — every service runs `npm` / `cargo` / `uv` audits, and a dependency-review leg
  fails the moment a PR *introduces* a vulnerable package.
- **Static analysis** — CodeQL (`security-extended`) over JavaScript/TypeScript, Python and Rust, on
  every PR, every push, and once a week.
- **Containers** — on `master`, images are built, **scanned with Trivy, and only pushed to GHCR if the
  scan passes** — never push first and scan later.
- **Supply chain** — every third-party action is pinned to a full commit SHA (enforced by a repo
  setting), and an **unmapped-path tripwire** fails the build if a file nobody mapped to a check ever
  gets touched.

And the release itself runs without anyone touching it: every push to `master` runs
**semantic-release** (work out the version → write the changelog → bump every manifest → tag →
publish), alongside a `cd-registry` job that rebuilds and pushes only the images whose source moved.

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
    The gate's decision logic, every leg, and the release/registry mechanics:
    [CI/CD Pipeline → The CI gate](../../dev/Developer-Guide/cicd/#the-ci-gate) and
    [→ CD workflows](../../dev/Developer-Guide/cicd/#cd-workflows). The versioning rules:
    [Commits & Semantic Release](../../dev/Developer-Guide/semantic-release/#the-release-pipeline).

